AB  - A comprehensive analysis of ship energy efficiency management has been undertaken, focusing on optimizing onboard energy utilization as evidenced by engine performance metrics. Fuel consumption, currently indicated by heavy fuel oil/fuel oil (HFO/FO) and diesel oil (DO) usage, is a key parameter in this evaluation. To enhance energy monitoring, a novel model leveraging the Internet of Things (IoT) has been developed and validated against the Automatic Identification System (AIS). This cyber-physical model empowers a more effective approach to ship energy efficiency management. Moreover, the integration of the proposed model with IoT marks a significant advancement in the field, offering robust reliability for energy consumption monitoring. The model's effectiveness has been rigorously validated through its application on a specific bulk carrier operated by NS United Kaiun Kaisha, Ltd., Japan. Located at Vietnam Maritime University (VMU), Haiphong City, Vietnam, and managed by VINIC shipping transportation company, the vessel served as a robust testbed for the proposed methodologies. The quantitative results showed that the energy consumption of both diesel engines and marine boiler have been saved and approached under 0.5 (Tons). Comparative analysis of the results with existing models employing alternative approaches reveals significant advantages in terms of accuracy and efficiency, demonstrating the potential of this novel approach for enhanced ship energy monitoring. © 2024 IEEE.
